05816nam a22009615i 9783110973976DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20112008gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831109739767 a10.1515/97831109739762doi  a(DE-B1597)57337  a(OCoLC)979596521  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPN6071.F33 ǂb L58 2008eb 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a809/.9335100aLives of Faust :bThe Faust Theme in Literature and Music. A Reader /ced. by Lorna Fitzsimmons.  a2. Aufl. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2011] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (507 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDe Gruyter Textbook0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is an interdisciplinary reader on the Faust theme in literature and music from the Reformation to the present. Essays by Faust scholars set the texts in context. Peter Werres introduces the collection with The Changing Faces of Dr. Faustus. Osman Durrani and Gerald Strauss discuss contexts of the Faust Book, given in the English translation The Historie of the Damnable Life and Deserved Death of Doctor John Faustus. David Wootton compares Marlowe’s Doctor Faustus and the English Faust Book. Klaus L. Berghahn’s analysis of transformations of the theme and seventeenth- and eighteenth-century performance announcements contextualize the popular Puppet-Play of Doctor Faust. Works of Faustian music include the ballad The Just Judgment of God shew’d upon Dr. John Faustus, Berlioz’s The Damnation of Faust, and Gounod’s Faust. Essays by Henry Bacon and Steven R. Cerf engage the Faust theme in Romantic music and twentieth-century opera. Osman Durrani introduces 19th-Century American Fausts, represented by Hawthorne’s The Birthmark, and excerpts from Ethan Brand and Melville’s Moby Dick. Faust themes in the 20th and 21st centuries are represented by Valéry’s My Faust, Shapiro’s The Progress of Faust, Osman Durrani’s overview of Faust globalized, and Paul M. Malone’s work on the Faust theme in rock opera. A reading list is included.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 4aFaust /i. d. Literatur. 4aFaust /i. d. Musik. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aFaust (literature).  aFaust (music).1 aBacon, Henry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerghahn, Klaus L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerlioz, Hector, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCerf, Steven R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurrani, Osman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzsimmons, Lorna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzsimmons, Lorna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGounod, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawthorne, Nathaniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalone, Paul M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMelville, Herman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShapiro, Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrauss, Gerald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aValéry, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWerres, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWootton, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA B